Boards get subjected to much higher temperatures
during manufacture, then they get washed with solvents
or soap and water to remove soldering flux.

So no, a trip through the dishwasher isn't going to
hurt a circuit board- as long as you DO NOT run it
through the dry cycle. Remove the board after the
rinse cycle and shake off as much water as you can,
then set it in front of a heat vent to dry. Ideally
you should use compressed air to blow underneath
components but warm air from your furnace works OK.
Setting it out in the sun will work even better, but
there's rather a lack of warm, sunny spots in the N.
Hemisphere in winter. ;)

Let the board dry for at least a day before
reinstalling it.

If you've seen &quot;Top rack dishwasher safe&quot; on stuff,
what that means is it won't melt in the heated dry
cycle in the top rack because it's far enough away
from the radiant heating element. You can wash it in
the bottom rack as long as you set it to not dry.

P.S. You can do other weird stuff with a dishwasher
like blanching corn and other vegetables, as long as
the rinse aid dispenser is empty. I don't think Jet
Dry would go too well with corn on the cob. ;) Don't
run your corn through the dry cycle. Dishwashers make
poor barbecue grills.

