&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WD-40 &gt;

WD-40 is commonly used on electric switchgear without problems. Whether it does any good other than lubrication of moving parts is not clear.

Greg's note is pretty much the whole story about washing. He's right that the boards are washed in a dishwasher-like process as they are made. Modern surface mount fluxes are a bit acidic as are the leaks from aluminum electrolytic capacitors. Hot water is best for removing the acids but it can leave its own residues. Distilled water and deionized water are sometimes used for final rinses. Dry alcohol, ethanol or isopropanol, can be used to dry up remaining water on a washed board but rubbing alcohol is wet and won't work. Waiting a day or so probably does as well. Rosin solder flux used for repair is best cleaned with alcohol. Water doesn't cut it.

The entire board is heated to well over the boiling point of water for the soldering process. Some parts may be added after the soldering operation and might contain plastics that are not made for solder temperatures. That's the reason for keeping away from a dry cycle on a washing machine.

