WD-40 is neither a solvent nor is it a lubricant.  It was formulated to remove
water - WD = Water Displacement.  40 = the 40th attempt to come up with
something that would do this.

WD-40 dries into a gunk that is hard to dissolve, remove, what have you.
Granted, it isn't conductive, but it is sticky gunk at the end of its drying cycle.

