I too have washed 100's of logic boards, PSUs, even floppy drives,
DAT, 8mm mechanisms... basically, everything I get in, I wash.

I use the laundry room tub with a hose attached to faucet, and hot
water.   I spray a little Simple Green on, say a motherboard, then I
use a fat paint brush to go over part to loosen up dirt, then rinse
with hose.  I put my thumb over hose to get a strong jet of water.
When the board is steaming warm and rinsed, I carefully shake all the
water off it (you have to have a feel for how to properly hold the
board so that when you shake it down, you don't flex it)... then lay
the board down on a towel... flipping it over in about 6 hours.. and
let it dry a good 24hr.

WD40 is highly NOT recommended..as any oil residue will only collect
dirt.   I'd sooner use Pledge than WD-40.

Alchohol is fine when the part is small and you need it quick, but
otherwise, just isn't ideal for part cleaning because you can't spray
it, it's not hot, and it's not cheap.

I use this method on everything.. however, with drive mechanisms,
one has to take a lot more care..   not spraying water into motors,
for example.   Cleaning off the old lube first... Relubing the mechs
correctly afterwards.. etc.

~ J
