I agree that &quot;electronics will dry quick&quot; when you put them in the sun
on a sunny warm day, especially if its a windy day too.  But the fact
remains that it will not be &quot;in seconds&quot; as it would if you were to
use Ethanol.  Nor will your board suffer from bird droppings or
urination habits of canines or sudden rainstorms by being outdoors.

No matter how you slice it, Ethanol is faster and easier (assuming you
have a bottle of it, like I do).  The only reason why you would want
to put your board in water, then apply soap, then scrub, then rinse,
then repeat for places you forgot, then rinse, then dry in the sun, is
simply if you do not have a bottle of Ethanol or have no means to buy
it.  Seriously, Ethanol is easy and effective.  I know because we use
it at work every single day on all our electronics devices.  We would
never put our electronics in a washing machine or sink simply because
the drying time is too long, and the fact is that Ethanol cleans the
board with less scrubbing effort too.  A soft bristle toothbrush and
Ethanol works wonders on a dirty circuit board!

I don't say this to hurt the feelings of others nor pooh-pooh their
ideas of washing machine or sink cleaning in water.  I just mention
this to reinforce the fact that, Ethanol would be easier and will dry
in &quot;seconds.&quot;  You the board-washers must therefore determine what
course of action is best for you.  I really couldn't care what your
ultimate choice is, as I make no money off your purchases of Ethanol
or Dish washing liquid!  :-)  Just offering my experience.
