Not sure. WD-40 does leave a residue, so perhaps
there was a *bridge* of liquid in places you didn't
clean off. I wouldn't spray any solvents on a mobo,
but radio shack used to, maybe still does, sell an
oxide cleaner in a can. Years ago a mobo that I had
(Tandy 2000) was acting flaky. I took it apart, pulled
all the socketed chips out (THOUGH LEAVING THEM NEXT
TO THE SOCKETS FROM WHICH THEY CAME) and sprayed it
all down. Worked like a charm.
As far as washing a mobo...why? If there was crud all
over it, I could see. Water and soap won't hurt it, I
even tossed a k/b in a basin full of hot water soap
and about a quart of ammonia (one of the_best solvents
around, though it takes time to do it's work), left it
for a few hours, rinsed, dried, and my keys were no
longer sticking. Usually it's a good idea to rattle
the keys while it's been soaking for a while to
dislodge any crud.

